\chapter{Land use and urban planning}
\label{chap:land_use_urban_planning}
\epigraph{The truth about a city's aspirations isn't found in its vision. 
It's found in its budget.}{Brent Toderian}
%\epigraph{Show me the incentive and I will show you the outcome.}{Charlie Munger}

The previous three chapters described sustainability challenges related to our 
dwellings, food, and transportation. 
A common element in all these sustainability challenges is how we use land.
We need \emph{places} for homes and to grow food and
we also allocate land for transportation systems. 
Moreover, how and where we choose to put each of these elements influences 
the overall need for transportation in human society.
For example, dwellings and businesses that are spread out across a large area will
require more transportation than if they were located close together.

This chapter examines two different aspects of land use.
The first aspect is the layout or arrangement of different uses of land.
Which is more sustainable: to group all the farms, forests, and cities so that 
each is as large as possible or is it better to intersperse many small farms, 
forests, and towns?
Whereas Chapter~\ref{chap:households} was concerned with the efficiency of individual
structures, this chapter considers dwellings and businesses collectively. 
The objective is to design cities and farms with sustainability in mind.
We consider the sustainability implications of spacing, density, and how 
transportation links between city elements are affected by layout.

The second aspect is one of allocation, that is, \emph{how much} of each of the 
different uses for land we will have.
Land can be used for agriculture, recreation, urban or suburban dwellings, or 
not allocated for direct human use, that is, left as wilderness.
Land is the source, directly or indirectly, for all our resources, the sink for
much of our waste, and where we ourselves live.
We need land to simultaneously satisfy many different functions, including provide 
enough resources, accept wastes, and provide ecosystem services.

The next sections deal with three major sustainability questions related to land use. 
``How do we use land?''
``What effects does our use of land have on the sustainability of human society?''
``How can we transition to more sustainable arrangements?''


