Figure~\ref{fig:USlanduse} shows how land is used in the United States. 
%Although proportions may be different in other economies, the categories are the same. 
There are 1.9 billion acres in the contiguous 48 states.
Of this total, agriculture takes the largest share, with grazing (34\%), 
forestry (28\%), and crop production (20.6\%) being the three largest uses. 
The four largest crops in the U.S. are wheat (32\% of total crops), corn (30\%),
soybeans (20\%), and cotton (10\%). That leaves just 8\% for everything else and,
indeed, ``food we eat'' is a small area in Figure \ref{fig:USlanduse}.
In contrast, the area where we live and work (red/pink areas) is a relatively small
69.4 million acres (3.65\%).
One key observation from Figure~\ref{fig:USlanduse} is that the U.S. is relatively 
sparsely populated.

Land use changes over time and tracking those changes is important for understanding
relationships between land use and climate change.
The data for surveys such as Figure~\ref{fig:USlanduse} are produced from satellite imagery.
The European Space Agency recently released a dataset for \emph{global} land use over
a 24-year period (1992-2015) as part of a climate change initiative (CCI).
The Inter-governmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) uses 9 categories for land-use
classification: 
agriculture, forest, grass, wetland, settlement, shrubland, sparse, bare, and water.
Analysis~\cite{Nowosad2019} of the CCI data reveals some trends related to land use change over time.
First, urban areas are continually growing and, basically, never shrink.
From 1992--2015, settlements gained 337,000 square kilometers, which is 0.23\%
of the Earth's land area, or about 0.01\% per year.

The source of land for urban growth is principally agricultural land.
However, to feed a growing population, \emph{net} agricultural land has had to 
increase. 
The increase comes, primarily, from forests being converted to agriculture.
Simultaneously, there there is also some (formerly) agricultural land being
reforested.
The net gain for agricultural land means that \emph{more} more forests are cleared
than the amount of agricultural land that is being reforested.
Altogether, humans altered almost 1\% of total land area per year (22\% in 24 years)
across all land-use categories.

Land is the primary source of energy, be it fossil fuel, biomass, or renewable. 
Wells or mines for fossil fuels are located in a \emph{place}.
Biomass has to be grown or harvested from a \emph{place} as well.
Renewables, such as hydro, solar photovoltaic, and wind power, are also located in
a \emph{places}.
In particular, for hydro, solar, and wind, correct siting is a key consideration
for how productive each power type will be.
Not all locations are suitable for hydro power. Or wind. Or solar.

Land is also a major carbon sink. 
Forests store a lot of carbon and reforestation is likely necessary for meeting
climate change limits, which makes continued \emph{deforestation} particularly 
alarming.
Land use affects and is affected by climate change. 
For instance, hotter, drier weather results in more frequent and severe wildfires.
Those fires destroy forests, release stored carbon, and contribute to further warming.

\subsection{Demand for land}
Demand for land is driven by increasing human population ($P$). 
(See Equation~\ref{eq:IPARC}.)
As mentioned in Chapter~\ref{chap:agriculture}, higher population drives agriculture,
and agriculture is \emph{the} most prevalent way we use land.
The land-use statistics presented in the section above show humans taking more
land for agriculture and for cities over time.
As farm land is degraded, humans move on and create more farm land, primarily 
from forests, but also from grass lands, shrub land, and sparsely vegetated land.
Some of the abandoned farm land regrows to forest.

Population growth leads directly to a need for more housing,
but not just any housing.
Another trend shown by land-use statistics is greater urbanization.
The demand for housing is disproportionately for urban housing
because of a long-term trend of migration to urban areas. 
Urban areas have much higher GDP per area.
Thus pursuit of wealth, that is, a desire for greater affluence ($A$) drives 
migration from rural areas to urban ones.

The other major factor of land use demand is for resources.
The resources could be energy. 
For example, about 30\% of the U.S. corn (maize) crop is converted into ethanol
to be blended with gasoline as a transportation fuel.
Or, the resources could be material
(see Figures~\ref{fig:total_material_use} and~\ref{fig:per_capita_material_use}).
A major example is timber, which is a key ingredient in construction and many
consumer goods.
One of the major causes of deforestation in the Amazon basin, for instance, is 
(mostly illegal) attempts to extract mineral wealth.
Thus, there is a strong demand for resources ($R$) to feed an ever-growing global 
economy.
Those on the lowest rungs of the socio-economic ladder have few options to 
improve their lives. 
They need places to live, food to eat, and income to purchases these and other goods.
They can move to urban areas to try to get work or they can try to extract (pun intended)
a living by farming or mining.
Unfortunately, the best lands have already been taken; what is available to the 
\emph{next} farmer or miner is typically of marginally \emph{lower} productivity.

Therefore, consistent with earlier chapters, the drivers for land use are the 
terms of the IPARC equation, ($P$), ($A$), and ($R$).

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Land use efficiency}
\label{sec:land_efficiency}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Since land is a limited resource, it makes sense to maximize the effective use 
of that resource, whether that's for food, housing, and/or ecosystem services.
Various metrics could be used to gauge the effectiveness of land use.
For example, with respect to agriculture, we could attempt to maximize
calories per acre, pounds of food per acre, number of people fed per acre, \emph{or} 
Joules per food calorie (that is, EROI). 

For cities, we could attempt to maximize population density, or we could minimize
metrics related to impact, or we could try to make cities as self-sufficient as 
possible, for example with respect to food or energy.
We might try to minimize the amount of transportation emissions within cities.
Or we might try to maximize urban GDP.

However, we also care about ecosystem service and the health of the environment 
that provides those ecosystem services.
We care about multifactor indices: biodiverstiy, wilderness, ecosystem services, 
air and water quality, etc.

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
Remember former U.S.\ representative Vernon Ehlers:
``you can never do only one thing.''
\end{mcframe}

One way to describe the tension between land use for human needs and devoting land
to preserving ecosystem services is sparing versus sharing~\cite{Fraanje2018}.
Land ``sparing'' seeks to minimize the amount of agricultural land needed for humans
but maximizing the productivity of that land, even if it means input-intensive farming
that results in less biodiversity \emph{on the farm}. 
Other land is ``spared'' and set aside for conservation.
Land ``sharing'' uses agricultural practices that are more eco-friendly to wildlife
species on the farm, but, because yields aren't as high, requires more total farm land.

